data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code in EF Core 10:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` now takes a regular lambda (not an expression tree)

Your expression-tree building code **won't compile** — the overload now accepts `Func<...>` instead of `Expression<Func<...>>`.

**Fix** — replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more manual `Expression.Call`/`Expression.Lambda` needed.

---

## 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified / use full path

Two sub-changes:

| Scenario | Old column name | New column name |
|----------|----------------|-----------------|
| `ShippingAddress.Street` + `BillingAddress.Street` | Both → `Street` (collision!) | `Street` and `Street1` |
| `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` (nested) | `BillingAddress_City` | `Payment_BillingAddress_City` |

**Fix** — if you have existing tables/migrations, pin the old names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old shorter name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

Or, if the old shared column was unintentional, just generate a new migration and update the database.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter containing potentially-redacted SQL for logging.

**Fix:**

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

The `logCommandText` value has inlined constants redacted unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging()` is on — use it instead of `command.CommandText` in your log output.
